      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Soak the fruit",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Combine the currants, sultanas, raisins, glace cherries, and mixed peel in a large bowl. Pour over the brandy, stir, cover, and leave overnight. The fruit will absorb most of the liquid.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Prepare the tin and mix the batter",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 150°C conventional (130°C fan). Line the base and sides of a deep 23 cm round tin with a double layer of baking paper; tie a double band of brown paper around the outside of the tin to insulate it. Beat the butter and dark brown sugar together until pale and creamy. Add the eggs one at a time, beating well after each. Stir in the treacle and golden syrup. Fold in the flour, ground almonds, mixed spice, and baking powder, then fold in the soaked fruit with any remaining brandy in the bowl.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake and cool",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Spoon the batter into the prepared tin and level the surface. Make a slight depression in the centre with the back of a spoon (this counteracts the rise and keeps the surface flat for icing). Bake for 3 to 3 hours 30 minutes, checking with a skewer from 2 hours 45 minutes. The cake is done when the skewer comes out clean and the top is deep brown. Leave to cool completely in the tin, then remove, wrap in greaseproof paper and foil, and store in a cool place. Feed with 2 tablespoons of brandy every 1 to 2 weeks.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
